<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-285-835  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 285 835.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Spectrum  Jan 1990 v27 n1 p52(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Medical electronics. (trends in magnetic resonance imaging,biomagnetism, and laser welding)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fitzgerald, Karen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Major advances in biomagnetism in 1989 attracted substantialinterest from the medical electronics community, while magneticstimulation, magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), and laser weldingalso make significant advances.andP;  Biomagnetism involves the sensingof miniscule magnetic fields in the heart and the brain with'superconducting quantum interference devices' (Squids).andP;  Themagnetic signals can be located with an accuracy of a fewmillimeters.andP;  Two vendors introduced biomagnetic systems with 37Squids that speed measurement of large areas of the brain.andO;Research is being pursued in the stimulation of hand and legmovements by applying highly controlled, intense magnetic fieldsto specific portions of the brain.andP;  Advances in MRI includeshorter testing duration, improved resolution, and fastergeneration of 3D images.andP;  Advances in laser welding and shock-wavelithotripsy are noted.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Medical DiagnosisMedical ResearchMagnetic FieldsDiagnostic EquipmentTrendsReview of Past YearResearch and Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Major 1989 events in medical electronics. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>